comment: Observed "Pressure Cooker Mode" begin at 20:50 from steerage after a very strong single minor around 20:42 that sent significant runoff down SV channel. Very quiet from 21:15 until a long series of increasingly powerful minors began around 00:30. Minors began to pick up vertical action, follow up and water volume at 01:00.  NV continuous water for at least 63min, SV tried to switch to steam as early as 01:42 but could not fully switch. NV and SV spent the last 20-25 minutes of water phase trading back and forth as primary water spouter. Both vents in steam at 02:19. .

Opal Pool continuing to have large bursts, though longer intervals of up to 10 minutes.  More vertical now, according to Joanne, than before, when bursting out over whole pool and onto boardwalk.  Watched until 1545.  Steve Eide there observing and taking pics.

"Waterfall Geyser" (= "North of Thumb Geyser").  Yay - my first Waterfall eruption!  Small bubbler on the western edge of Waterfall's pool (the easternmost of the 3 features to the west of Waterfall) was active all afternoon.  It got swamped by a Waterfall Geyser basin filling event at 1726 - pool engaged in slight roiling.  Eruption from 1731 to 1810 (see attachments for still photos and video compilation).  Bursting from 2 vents - usually one at a time.  Highest bursts maybe ~7 feet high.  Eruption runoff cascaded over rocky outcrop into Thumb Geyser - that basin filled up pretty well.  Waterfall Geyser's basin slowly draining at 1813; back to pre-eruption pool level at 1816; pool level was way lower by 1820, partly exposing the large, central, irregularly-shaped vent area.

I warched for about 55-60 minutes before the eruption so I think the intervals are well over an hour.  The pool was in light overflow all the time I watched.  30 minutes after the euption the pool was not in overflow yet.
